    the ordered pair of a and b is an object
    the ordered pair of a and b is an element of A \SETprod B
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class then (v0 \SETprod v1 is empty iff (v0 is empty or v1 is empty))
Proof:
  if A \SETprod B is empty then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    it is wrong that A is empty and it is wrong that B is empty
    a is an element of A and b is an element of B
    the ordered pair of a and b is an element of A \SETprod B
    falsity holds
  Qed.
  if A is empty or B is empty then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    it is wrong that A \SETprod B is empty
    c is an element of A \SETprod B
    for some v0, v0 is an element of A and for some v1, v1 is an element of B and c is equal to the ordered pair of v0 and v1
    it is wrong that A is empty and it is wrong that B is empty
    falsity holds
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, if v0 is an object and v1 is an object then \SETsingleton{ v0 } \SETprod \SETsingleton{ v1 } is equal to \SETsingleton{ the ordered pair of v0 and v1 }
Proof:
  \SETsingleton{ a } \SETprod \SETsingleton{ b } is a subclass of \SETsingleton{ the ordered pair of a and b }
  Proof:
    c is an element of \SETsingleton{ a } \SETprod \SETsingleton{ b }
    a' is an element of \SETsingleton{ a } and b' is an element of \SETsingleton{ b } and c is equal to the ordered pair of a' and b'
    a' is equal to a and b' is equal to b
    c is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    c is an element of \SETsingleton{ the ordered pair of a and b }
  Qed.
  \SETsingleton{ the ordered pair of a and b } is a subclass of \SETsingleton{ a } \SETprod \SETsingleton{ b }
  Proof:
    c is an element of \SETsingleton{ the ordered pair of a and b }
    c is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    a is an element of \SETsingleton{ a } and b is an element of \SETsingleton{ b }
    c is an element of \SETsingleton{ a } \SETprod \SETsingleton{ b }
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, for all v3, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class and v3 is a class and (it is wrong that v0 is empty and it is wrong that v1 is empty and it is wrong that v2 is empty and it is wrong that v3 is empty) then (if v0 \SETprod v2 is equal to v1 \SETprod v3 then (v0 is equal to v1 and v2 is equal to v3))
Proof:
  A \SETprod B is equal to A' \SETprod B'
  A is a subclass of A' and B is a subclass of B'
  Proof:
    a is an element of A and b is an element of B
    the ordered pair of a and b is an element of A \SETprod B
    the ordered pair of a and b is an element of A' \SETprod B'
    a is an element of A' and b is an element of B'
  Qed.
  A' is a subclass of A and B' is a subclass of B
  Proof:
    a is an element of A' and b is an element of B'
    the ordered pair of a and b is an element of A' \SETprod B'
    the ordered pair of a and b is an element of A \SETprod B
    a is an element of A and b is an element of B
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class then (if v0 is a subclass of v1 then v0 \SETprod v2 is a subclass of v1 \SETprod v2)
Proof:
  A is a subclass of B
  x is an element of A \SETprod C
  a is an element of A and c is an element of C and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and c
  a is an element of B
  the ordered pair of a and c is an element of B \SETprod C
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, for all v3, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class and v3 is a class then (if it is wrong that v0 is empty and it is wrong that v1 is empty then (v0 \SETprod v1 is a subclass of v2 \SETprod v3 iff (v0 is a subclass of v2 and v1 is a subclass of v3)))
Proof:
  if A \SETprod A' is a subclass of B \SETprod B' then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    for all v0, if v0 is an element of A then for all v1, if v1 is an element of A' then (v0 is an element of B and v1 is an element of B')
    Proof:
      a is an element of A and a' is an element of A'
      the ordered pair of a and a' is an element of A \SETprod A'
      the ordered pair of a and a' is an element of B \SETprod B'
      a is an element of B and a' is an element of B'
    Qed.
  Qed.
  if A is a subclass of B and A' is a subclass of B' then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod A'
    a is an element of A and a' is an element of A' and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and a'
    a is an element of B and a' is an element of B'
    the ordered pair of a and a' is an element of B \SETprod B'
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class then v0 \SETunion v1 \SETprod v2 is equal to v0 \SETprod v2 \SETunion v1 \SETprod v2
Proof:
  A \SETunion B \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETprod C \SETunion B \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETunion B \SETprod C
    y is an element of A \SETunion B and c is an element of C and x is equal to the ordered pair of y and c
    y is an element of A or y is an element of B
    if y is an element of A then (x is an element of A \SETprod C and (if y is an element of B then x is an element of B \SETprod C))
    x is an element of A \SETprod C or x is an element of B \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod C \SETunion B \SETprod C
  Qed.
  A \SETprod C \SETunion B \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETunion B \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod C \SETunion B \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod C or x is an element of B \SETprod C
    c is an object and y is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of y and c
    (y is an element of A or y is an element of B) and c is an element of C
    y is an element of A \SETunion B
    x is an element of A \SETunion B \SETprod C
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class then v0 \SETprod v1 \SETunion v2 is equal to v0 \SETprod v1 \SETunion v0 \SETprod v2
Proof:
  A \SETprod B \SETunion C is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETunion A \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETunion C
    a is an element of A and y is an element of B \SETunion C and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and y
    y is an element of B or y is an element of C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B or x is an element of A \SETprod C
    Proof:
      if y is an element of B then (x is an element of A \SETprod B and (if y is an element of C then x is an element of A \SETprod C))
    Qed.
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETunion A \SETprod C
  Qed.
  A \SETprod B \SETunion A \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETunion C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETunion A \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B or x is an element of A \SETprod C
    a is an object and y is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and y
    a is an element of A and (y is an element of B or y is an element of C)
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETunion C
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class then v0 \SETintersect v1 \SETprod v2 is equal to v0 \SETprod v2 \SETintersect v1 \SETprod v2
Proof:
  A \SETintersect B \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETprod C \SETintersect B \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETintersect B \SETprod C
    y is an element of A \SETintersect B and c is an element of C and x is equal to the ordered pair of y and c
    y is an element of A and y is an element of B
    x is an element of A \SETprod C and x is an element of B \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod C \SETintersect B \SETprod C
  Qed.
  A \SETprod C \SETintersect B \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETintersect B \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod C \SETintersect B \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod C and x is an element of B \SETprod C
    y is an object and z is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of y and z
    y is an element of A and y is an element of B and z is an element of C
    y is an element of A \SETintersect B
    x is an element of A \SETintersect B \SETprod C
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class then v0 \SETprod v1 \SETintersect v2 is equal to v0 \SETprod v1 \SETintersect v0 \SETprod v2
Proof:
  A \SETprod B \SETintersect C is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETintersect A \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETintersect C
    a is an element of A and b is an element of B \SETintersect C and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    b is an element of B and b is an element of C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B and x is an element of A \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETintersect A \SETprod C
  Qed.
  A \SETprod B \SETintersect A \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETintersect C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETintersect A \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B and x is an element of A \SETprod C
    y is an object and z is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of y and z
    y is an element of A and z is an element of B and z is an element of C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETintersect C
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class then v0 \SETdiff v1 \SETprod v2 is equal to v0 \SETprod v2 \SETdiff v1 \SETprod v2
Proof:
  A \SETdiff B \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETprod C \SETdiff B \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETdiff B \SETprod C
    a is an element of A \SETdiff B and c is an element of C and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and c
    a is an element of A and it is wrong that a is an element of B
    x is an element of A \SETprod C and it is wrong that x is an element of B \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod C \SETdiff B \SETprod C
  Qed.
  A \SETprod C \SETdiff B \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETdiff B \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod C \SETdiff B \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod C and it is wrong that x is an element of B \SETprod C
    a is an element of A and c is an element of C and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and c
    it is wrong that a is an element of B
    Proof:
      if a is an element of B then x is an element of B \SETprod C
    Qed.
    a is an element of A \SETdiff B
    x is an element of A \SETdiff B \SETprod C
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class then v0 \SETprod v1 \SETdiff v2 is equal to v0 \SETprod v1 \SETdiff v0 \SETprod v2
Proof:
  A \SETprod B \SETdiff C is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETdiff A \SETprod C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff C
    a is an element of A and b is an element of B \SETdiff C and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    b is an element of B and it is wrong that b is an element of C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B and it is wrong that x is an element of A \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff A \SETprod C
  Qed.
  A \SETprod B \SETdiff A \SETprod C is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETdiff C
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff A \SETprod C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B and it is wrong that x is an element of A \SETprod C
    a is an object and b is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    a is an element of A and b is an element of B and it is wrong that b is an element of C
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff C
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, for all v3, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class and v3 is a class then (if (it is wrong that v0 is empty and it is wrong that v1 is empty) or (it is wrong that v2 is empty and it is wrong that v3 is empty) then (v0 \SETprod v1 is equal to v2 \SETprod v3 iff (v0 is equal to v2 and v1 is equal to v3)))
Proof:
  if A \SETprod A' is equal to B \SETprod B' then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    (it is wrong that A is empty and it is wrong that A' is empty) iff (it is wrong that B is empty and it is wrong that B' is empty)
    for all v0, if v0 is an element of A then for all v1, if v1 is an element of A' then (v0 is an element of B and v1 is an element of B')
    Proof:
      a is an element of A and a' is an element of A'
      the ordered pair of a and a' is an element of A \SETprod A'
      x is an element of B \SETprod B' and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and a'
      a is an element of B and a' is an element of B'
    Qed.
    A is a subclass of B and A' is a subclass of B'
    Proof:
      it is wrong that A is empty and it is wrong that A' is empty
    Qed.
    for all v0, if v0 is an element of B then for all v1, if v1 is an element of B' then (v0 is an element of A and v1 is an element of A')
    Proof:
      b is an element of B and b' is an element of B'
      the ordered pair of b and b' is an element of B \SETprod B'
      x is an element of A \SETprod A' and x is equal to the ordered pair of b and b'
      the ordered pair of b and b' is an element of A \SETprod A'
    Qed.
    B is a subclass of A and B' is a subclass of A'
    Proof:
      it is wrong that B is empty and it is wrong that B' is empty
    Qed.
  Qed.
  if A is equal to B and A' is equal to B' then the thesis holds
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, for all v3, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class and v3 is a class then v0 \SETprod v2 \SETintersect v1 \SETprod v3 is equal to v0 \SETintersect v1 \SETprod v2 \SETintersect v3
Proof:
  A \SETprod B \SETintersect A' \SETprod B' is a subclass of A \SETintersect A' \SETprod B \SETintersect B'
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETintersect A' \SETprod B'
    x is an element of A \SETprod B and x is an element of A' \SETprod B'
    a is an object and b is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    a is an element of A and a is an element of A' and (b is an element of B and b is an element of B')
    a is an element of A \SETintersect A' and b is an element of B \SETintersect B'
    x is an element of A \SETintersect A' \SETprod B \SETintersect B'
  Qed.
  A \SETintersect A' \SETprod B \SETintersect B' is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETintersect A' \SETprod B'
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETintersect A' \SETprod B \SETintersect B'
    a is an object and b is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    a is an element of A \SETintersect A' and b is an element of B \SETintersect B'
    a is an element of A and a is an element of A' and (b is an element of B and b is an element of B')
    x is an element of A \SETprod B and x is an element of A' \SETprod B'
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETintersect A' \SETprod B'
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, for all v3, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class and v3 is a class then v0 \SETprod v2 \SETunion v1 \SETprod v3 is a subclass of v0 \SETunion v1 \SETprod v2 \SETunion v3
Proof:
  x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETunion A' \SETprod B'
  x is an element of A \SETprod B or x is an element of A' \SETprod B'
  a is an object and b is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
  (a is an element of A or a is an element of A') and (b is an element of B or b is an element of B')
  a is an element of A \SETunion A' and b is an element of B \SETunion B'
  x is an element of A \SETunion A' \SETprod B \SETunion B'
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, for all v1, for all v2, for all v3, if v0 is a class and v1 is a class and v2 is a class and v3 is a class then v0 \SETprod v2 \SETdiff v1 \SETprod v3 is equal to v0 \SETprod v2 \SETdiff v3 \SETunion v0 \SETdiff v1 \SETprod v2
Proof:
  A \SETprod B \SETdiff A' \SETprod B' is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETdiff B' \SETunion A \SETdiff A' \SETprod B
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff A' \SETprod B'
    x is an element of A \SETprod B and it is wrong that x is an element of A' \SETprod B'
    a is an element of A and b is an element of B and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    it is wrong that (a is an element of A' and b is an element of B')
    it is wrong that a is an element of A' or it is wrong that b is an element of B'
    a is an element of A \SETdiff A' or b is an element of B \SETdiff B'
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff B' or x is an element of A \SETdiff A' \SETprod B
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff B' \SETunion A \SETdiff A' \SETprod B
  Qed.
  A \SETprod B \SETdiff B' \SETunion A \SETdiff A' \SETprod B is a subclass of A \SETprod B \SETdiff A' \SETprod B'
  Proof:
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff B' \SETunion A \SETdiff A' \SETprod B
    x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff B' or x is an element of A \SETdiff A' \SETprod B
    a is an object and b is an object and x is equal to the ordered pair of a and b
    Proof:
      for some v0, for some v1, v0 is a class and v1 is a class and x is an element of v0 \SETprod v1
    Qed.
    (a is an element of A and b is an element of B \SETdiff B') or (a is an element of A \SETdiff A' and b is an element of B)
    if a is an element of A and b is an element of B \SETdiff B' then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      a is an element of A and b is an element of B
      x is an element of A \SETprod B
      it is wrong that b is an element of B'
      it is wrong that x is an element of A' \SETprod B'
      x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff A' \SETprod B'
    Qed.
    if a is an element of A \SETdiff A' and b is an element of B then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      a is an element of A and b is an element of B
      x is an element of A \SETprod B
      it is wrong that a is an element of A'
      it is wrong that x is an element of A' \SETprod B'
      x is an element of A \SETprod B \SETdiff A' \SETprod B'
    Qed.
  Qed.
Qed.

